  <div class="prose">
    <h2>In the Chain</h2>
    <p>The Opto is the last compressor in the vocal chain, after the WA76. Vocals arrive already transient-controlled by the 1176, and the optical circuit applies slow, program-dependent leveling — the kind of compression you feel but do not hear. It also sees use on guitar when the source needs smoothing rather than peak control.</p>

    <h2>Controls</h2>
    <p>Two knobs. Peak Reduction controls how much signal hits the optical cell — more reduction means more compression, but the ratio shifts with the signal level because that is how optical compressors work. Gain makes up the output level. The LIMIT/COMPRESS switch changes the knee: COMPRESS for gentle leveling on vocals, LIMIT for harder ratio on guitar transients. The VU meter toggles between gain reduction and output level.</p>

    <h2>Character</h2>
    <p>Optical compression is inherently slow and nonlinear. The photocell and light-dependent resistor create attack and release curves that no VCA or FET circuit can replicate — the release time depends on how long the signal has been compressing. Short bursts release fast. Sustained notes release slowly. This is what makes an LA2A-style compressor sound like it is breathing with the performance rather than clamping down on it. The Audioscape build uses the same T4B optical cell topology as the original Teletronix units. It is the most transparent piece of outboard in the rack — its job is to make everything that came before it sit perfectly in the mix without anyone noticing it is there.</p>
